This place has two rooms, one is a bar/kitchen, the other a music hall and sit down w/bar. The band playing that night was instrumental only and they were good. We ate and drank as we watched the show. We looked at the menu while the band played on. I had the steak, chicken, and pork tacos, my battle buddy had the wings and another round of brewskowskis.  Wish I could tell you the name of the band but the guy on the microphone mumbled and held it so far from his face we couldn't understand what he was saying. Regardless of that , the music was goooooood! The talent was there, and they looked like they were having fun on stage. The crowd got into the vibe, and the solos each member got to show off a little bit (except the drummer) hahaha!

On Frenchman. Big place. Got some drinks and looked at the menu. You never know in tourist areas if food is any good. Looking at the menu... pizza, salads, tacos, burritos???? Iffy. Sketchy? Talked to an employee who recommended food and told us where the Brazilian chef worked before, which made us comfortable to order. I had a taco salad bowl and Honduran tamale. Babycakes had 3 tacos. The Honduran Tamale is wrapped in banana leaf. Different from Mexican tamales. Usually more masa, less meat. This had more masa, but a lot of pork inside. The creamy salsa verde was really HOT! The tamale was great, along with the Pico de Gallo and hominy, or rice? that it comes with. The beef taco salad was Awesome!! Except for the shell, which I'm guessing is a premade, baked shell. NOT GOOD!! The beef in it was not ground, it was chunks. GREAT!! NOT dry, Flavorful, mixed with lettuce, tomato, etc... with more salsa verde made it super... I tried Babycakes tacos, and the Chicken and beef were good. She did not like the pork and pineapple (it was passable to me). Prices on alcohol were kind of high, but it's Frenchman St. Only ONE washroom, no paper towels.

At the door giant  NYC style slices of pizza were being sold for $4.00. Pizza was hot and fresh, with attendants replenishing constantly due to demand. Comfortable seating was available. The only complaint I have  is the availability of parmesan cheese and pepper (Very necessary in my book). I had to wait on the bar staff to give it to me after I received my food. I'm aware that more than pizza is served, but if you have a booth at the door, why not have these items at the door. Overall, I will still come back. 🍕

my girlfriend and I travel to New Orleans often to relax and have a little fun. over the last 4 times I've been dying to try this place. this past Monday night (1/15/18) we finally made it for the first time. we walked in I sat at the bar and immediately began looking at the menu. My girlfriend asked where the restroom was and the  bartender (short blonde girl who never introduced herself) in a very condensing tone said "bathrooms are for customers only." at this point, I explained we had every intention of ordering food. she then said "it's right there" in the rudest way possible. we both had some choice words for her and we apologized for that, however this girls attitude singlehandedly ruined my experience at this establishment.  I never get to try the crawfish tacos I been dying for almost a year to eat all due to her horrible service. I tried calling and speaking to a manager no one answers the number provided on Google. wish I could give no stars

The food here was HANDS-DOWN the best food I had in NOLA. We ate at expensive restaurants, tried all of the "must-trys" with the most Yelp and Google reviews... you name it. None of those compare to Favela Chic. The food is absolutely amazing. We ordered the cheesesteak grinder and shrimp tacos. We spent some time chatting with the chef, Raymond, as well as the bartender (forget his name, but I remember him telling us he lived in Cali before moving to NOLA!). We heard that the Pizza is also amazing, but they ran out before we arrived - must be a good sign :)  Viva ! Obrigada por tudo!

Despite that, the wings were good. We had a couple of drinks and they were well served.
